1 lease and to the cost of providing for the operation of the television or related
2 facilities not only appropriations which may be made to it from state funds,
3 from time to time, but also contributions, gifts, matching funds, devises, and
4 bequests from any source, whether federal or state, and whether public or
5 private, so long as the same are not conditioned upon any improper use of the
6 television or related facilities in a manner inconsistent with the provisions of
7 this subsection.
8 (4) The state board may, on the recommendation and with the advice of the chief state
9 school officer, prescribe, print, publish, and distribute at public expense such
10 administrative regulations, courses of study, curriculums, bulletins, programs,
11 outlines, reports, and placards as each deems necessary for the efficient
12 management, control, and operation of the schools and programs under its
13 jurisdiction. All administrative regulations published or distributed by the board
14 shall be enclosed in a booklet or binder on which the words "informational copy"
15 shall be clearly stamped or printed.
16 (5) Upon the recommendation of the chief state school officer or his or her designee,
17 the state board shall establish policy or act on all matters relating to programs,
18 services, publications, capital construction and facility renovation, equipment,
19 litigation, contracts, budgets, and all other matters which are the administrative
20 responsibility of the Department of Education.
21 (6) On or after June 27, 2025, the state board shall not impose any new reporting
22 requirement upon public schools or public school districts that is not expressly
23 authorized by state statute or federal law.
24 Section 5. Whereas it is paramount that schools in the Commonwealth have the
25 best leadership possible, an emergency is declared to exist, and Section 3 of this Act
26 takes effect upon its passage and approval by the Governor or upon its otherwise
27 becoming a law.
